Tldr- DONT SPEND YOUR MONEY HERE.  I am so embarrassed to have brought my friend here. A friend of mine who doesnt live in the neighborhood was craving pizza and we walked ten min out of our way to come here based on our experiences at other Artichoke locations. She ordered a vodka sicilian for her first slice; i wasnt quite hungry at the moment so I was holding off to join her for her second slice. Thank goodness she ordered only one slice first because the slice was BURNT at the bottom (you couldnt tell through the counter window bc of the sauce). It was so burnt it was like cardboard and she had trouble using fork and knife to cut off a piece. Also, we could clearly see once she turned the piece over that the bottom was nearly charred. When she told the guy who worked there he dismissed her and said that is the way it is supposed to be. I told him to taste the piece for himself because it was CLEARLY BURNED to the point it should not be consumed. He kept dismissing our comment, saying that the burntness was part of the vodka pizza (sorry...NO). He refused to give her another unburned piece of pizza or a refund, essentially insinuating that he couldnt help that she didnt like the taste of burned pizza. When we saw pretty quickly that this was not a fight worth fighting, we just walked out because arguing for 15min over a clearly burned pizza was not worth the $5.50. We walked over to a place that served a basic NY slice with no frills for half the price and a crust that was not burned.  Keep in mind that this place claims to be a "gourmet" pizza joint and charges $2 more per slice than the surrounding places... something is off when burnt pizza is served. Not only that, something is off when a so called gourmet pizza place can't afford courteous service. In short, DONT SPEND YOUR MONEY HERE. And i had to apologize profusely to my hungry friend for making us walk out of our way for burned pizza. Don't waste your time like we did.

I've long bemoaned the rising prices of slices of pizza; from a single buck, the price has slowly crept up into the two dollar stratosphere, with most slices going for more than that. Imagine my surprise when I willingly shelled out $6 for a single slice of pizza. Once the slice came out of the oven and onto my plates (! two of them), I started to understand why this pizza demanded the premium price. The slice was almost the size of two regular slices and had a thick crust, covered in a creamy, cheesy sauce all over the slice.  With slices of Artichoke Basille's pizza, the saying "less is more" comes to mind. Although the concept of cream, cheese, artichokes and bread sounds like a wonderful combination, when put together in the proportions of the Artichoke Pizza Slice, they become overpowering and leave me slightly nauseous at 2/3 of the way through the slice (which may be about 2 full slices of a normal pie). That being said, perhaps having this slice in two settings, or very very slowly would be advised.  Other things to note: theres limited seating here (2 tables and a counter to stand at) and they only accept cash (ATM helpfully next to the counter)

My fiancé and I stayed in Brooklyn for our NY trip and just happened across this place while walking around. I'm so glad we did, too! The place itself is small but the pie slices are huge...everything one would imagine NY pizza to be if you've never been there before. It was so good we ended up eating there twice during our trip. The first time we shared their famous artichoke slice (we had already eaten before but were indulging) and it was absolutely amazing! The flavors explode in your mouth causing an instant foodgasm. The crust is absolutely perfect and I'm generally not one who likes crust. Overall, the pizza is light and doesn't weigh you down, so to speak. The people are really friendly, too, and make sure the pie is hot for you. It makes me wish I lived there since I found my new favorite pizza place. Definitely worth 5 stars or more!
